✅ QUESTION 3: Limited Dependent Variable Models
(A) Setup
data3 <- read.csv("bank.csv")

data3$y <- ifelse(data3$y == "yes", 1, 0)
 
(B) Estimation
LPM
lpm <- lm(y ~ age + balance + campaign + pdays + previous, data=data3)
summary(lpm)
Logit
logit <- glm(y ~ age + balance + campaign + pdays + previous, 
             data=data3, family=binomial)
summary(logit)
 
(C) Marginal Effects
install.packages("margins")
library(margins)
margins(logit)
👉 Interpretation:
•	Positive → increases probability
•	Negative → decreases probability
 
(D) Model Comparison
Predictions
# Logit predictions
data3$prob <- predict(logit, type="response")

# Classification
data3$pred <- ifelse(data3$prob > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Confusion matrix
table(data3$y, data3$pred)
Accuracy
mean(data3$y == data3$pred)
 
Key Theory Lines (WRITE THESE IN EXAM)
•	LPM → simple but heteroscedastic, predictions outside 0–1
•	Logit → bounded (0–1), non-linear, more realistic
•	Logit preferred due to theoretical validity
 


